{
  "doc_id": "13289",
  "text": "Several studies indicate that the protein kinase activation events that are initiated by I/R can be reproduced by oxidative agents [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] suggesting that ROS/RNS are among the principal responsible for the reversible protein kinase activation observed subsequently to I/R. In fact, ROS/RNS may induce either reversible or irreversible oxidation of proteins/enzymes (Fig. 4) . Reversible modifications include, for instance, modifications of cysteine residues such as disulfides, sulfenamides, protein SNO and S-glutathionylation. Sulfenamides can be further oxidized to sulfinic or sulfonic acid, which are generally considered irreversible modifications [CITATION_6] . Besides cysteine residues, other targets of ROS may be iron-sulfide centers and zincfinger domains of proteins.",
